      <scopecontent id="aspace_533840e6c3dc49fa8b00ed3a9bb41399">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The Asa Burton Papers consist of sermons and writings, which document Burton's service to the Congregational church in Thetford, Vermont, and contain observations on his life and church and town history. The papers contain an autobiographical memoir as well as essays on Thetford's society and politics. Burton records the developing political tensions between Federalists and Republicans and the manner in which the chruch and its mnister were drawn into political strife. It contains Burton's exposition of a chruch trial involving political partisans Beriah Loomis and Asher Chamberlain. Burton's sermons on the anniversaries of his twenty-fifth and fiftieth year in the ministry and other special occasions are also included in the papers. Material from some folders is transcribed in published edtion of Burton's memoirs and writings, edied by Charles Latham Jr.</p>
         <p>The Burton manuscripts were donated to the Yale University Library by Ruth Adams in 1954. They were transferred frm the Miscellaneous Manuscripts Collection (MS 352) in 1985. Additional Burton papers were given to Vassar College.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <bioghist id="aspace_09033c7039d4a7291c6c522d285726c8">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Asa Burton was born in Stonington, Connecticut, and, at age 16, moved to Norwich, Vermont. In 1777 he graduated from Dartmouth and was ordained in 1779 at Thetford, Vermont, where he became pastor for life. Burton was best known as a teacher of theology.</p>  
      </bioghist>
